ms) should be prominently featured, perhaps within the respective sprint cards or as a concluding statement for the roadmap section, using a style similar to the `.perf-badge` in the footer.\n    *   **Strategic Value and Leadership**\n        *   A concluding `h2` title.\n        *   Present the \"Why this strategy positions you as a leader\" argument as a compelling text block, possibly using emphasis (bolding) on key points.\n\n**Style Design Language:**\n\n1.  **Visual Design Approach**: Maintain the \"Modern & Stylish\" and \"Professional & Technical\" aesthetic of the Asio site. The design should be clean, high-contrast, and utilize ample whitespace to enhance readability, while retaining the energetic and \"wow factor\" achieved through subtle glows and gradients.\n\n2.  **Aesthetic Goal**: \"Premium, cutting-edge technical documentation.\" The page should exude competence, foresight, and a sophisticated understanding of web performance and modern architecture.\n\n3.  **Color Scheme**: Strictly adhere to the existing CSS variables:\n    *   Backgrounds: `--bg`, `--bg2`, `--bg3`, `--surface`.\n    *   Text: `--text` for primary content, `--muted` for secondary/explanatory text.\n    *   Accents: `--accent` (orange) and `--accent2` (purple) for highlights, interactive elements, and visual interest. `--green` for positive indicators (like performance targets).\n    *   Glow: Utilize `var(--glow)` for subtle visual depth.\n\n4.  **Typography Style**:\n    *   Headings (`h1`, `h2`, `h3`, `h4`): Use `var(--font-head)` ('Syne', sans-serif) with bold weights (`700`, `800`) and appropriate font sizes from the existing CSS (`section-title`).\n    *   Body text and paragraphs: Use `var(--font-body)` ('DM Sans', sans-serif) for high readability.\n    *   Code snippets or technical terms (if inline): Consider `code` or `pre` tags with a slightly muted background and a monospace font if not explicitly defined by `--font-body`.\n\n5.  **Spacing and Layout Principles**:\n    *   **Generous Whitespace**: Employ ample padding and margins, especially around sections and content blocks, to prevent visual clutter and improve comprehension.\n    *   **Content Centering**: Use the `.container` class to ensure content is well-aligned and readable on wider screens.\n    *   **Responsiveness**: The layout must be fully responsive, utilizing existing `grid-2`, `grid-3` classes and media queries defined in the `overall_app_intent` to adapt gracefully to mobile devices.\n\n**Component Guidelines:**\n\n1.  **Reused UI Components**:\n    *   **Navigation & Footer**: Include the exact HTML and CSS for the `nav` and `footer` elements.\n    *   **Sections**: Use the `.section` class for major content blocks.\n    *   **Headings**: Use `.section-title`, `.section-sub` for main headings and descriptions.\n    *   **Tags**: Utilize the `.tag` class for contextual labels (e.g., \"Technical Strategy\").\n    *   **Cards**: Adapt the `.card` or `.feat-card` styling for presenting individual roadmap sprints or key diagnostic points in a visually appealing grid.\n    *   **Lists**: Standard `ul` and `li` elements for bulleted information, potentially styled with custom markers similar to `.mastery-list li::before` for visual appeal.\n    *   **Buttons**: If any calls to action are needed within the document (e.g., \"Download PDF\"), use `.btn`, `.btn-primary`, or `.btn-outline` styles.\n    *   **Performance Badges**: Style important performance metrics (`LCP < 1.5s`, `80% image reduction`, `lead processing < 50ms`) using or adapting the `.perf-badge` style.\n\n2.  **Visual Enhancements**:\n    *   Apply subtle `fade-in` animations to major content blocks or `card` elements to provide a dynamic and engaging user experience, similar to the existing site.\n    *   Incorporate gradients and box-shadows (e.g., `--glow`) where appropriate to maintain the branded visual depth and modern feel.\n\ndetailed_migration_strategy_text: {{\"type\":\"in\",\"path\":\"node_step